## 4. Design direction: world-class ≠ busy

**Professional for your audience** means: calm, confident, lots of whitespace, **real photography**, clear type — not animation for its own sake.

**Parallax & thread/needle — use as accent, once:**

| Idea | Verdict |
|------|--------|
| Subtle **thread line** (SVG) weaving through section dividers on scroll | Strong brand metaphor for Stitch & Stone |
| **Needle** as small loader or one hero moment | Good if tiny and elegant |
| Full-page parallax, heavy scroll effects | Avoid — feels 2015, hurts mobile, slows load |

**Visual language for Stitch & Stone:**

- **Stone:** warm grays, off-white, concrete/slate — stability, Michigan, “built to last”
- **Stitch:** one accent — copper, terracotta, or deep teal thread (pick one, use sparingly)
- **Typography:** one distinctive serif or humanist sans for headlines + clean sans for body (no generic “startup” fonts)
- **Motion:** CSS scroll-linked SVG stroke animation for a thread path — **no JS required** for a beautiful effect

**World-class reference mindset:** Think premium packaging brands + boutique agencies, not Vistaprint or 4imprint catalog sites.

