## 5. Stay organized: copies, backups, rebrand-safe

You said you want backups if anything happens — **treat the website like a business asset**, not a single folder on one laptop.

**Folder / repo structure (fits your empty `Logo-Clothing-Shop-FOUNDATION` repo):**

```text
/
├── site/                 # Live website (HTML/CSS, later maybe Astro)
├── content/
│   ├── copy/             # All page text in .md — survives redesigns
│   ├── case-studies/
│   └── blog/             # Optional later
├── brand/
│   ├── logo-current/
│   ├── logo-stitch-stone/  # Future rebrand assets
│   ├── colors.md
│   ├── fonts.md
│   └── photo-guidelines.md
├── prompts/              # Your AI prompt library (copy + code)
├── backups/              # Optional: dated exports (see below)
└── README.md             # “How this project works” for future you
```

**Backup rules (simple, non-negotiable):**

1. **GitHub (or GitLab)** — every save is history; that’s backup #1  
2. **Second copy** — GitHub on your account + occasional zip to Google Drive or OneDrive (`backups/2026-06-24-site.zip`)  
3. **Domain + DNS** at Cloudflare or registrar — you own it, not your host  
4. **Copy lives in Markdown** — if the site burns down, you still have every word  
5. **Brand assets** only in `/brand` — never only inside random design tool exports  

**Hosting:** Netlify or Cloudflare Pages connected to Git — push = deploy + cloud copy. No “only on my computer.”

